\begin_layout Theorem
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:parallelogram"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(V,\pnorm{\cdot}{}\right)$
\end_inset

 be a normed vector space.
 The norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{\cdot}{}$
\end_inset

 is induced by an inner product if and only if the parallelogram identity
 is satisfied.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
First suppose that the norm 
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{\cdot}{}$
\end_inset

 is induced by the inner product 
\begin_inset Formula $\innerproduct{\cdot}{\cdot}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\pnorm{\frac{v+w}{2}}{}^{2}+\pnorm{\frac{v-w}{2}}{}^{2} & =\innerproduct{\frac{v+w}{2}}{\frac{v+w}{2}}+\innerproduct{\frac{v-w}{2}}{\frac{v-w}{2}}\\
 & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\innerproduct vv+2\innerproduct vw+\innerproduct ww\right)+\frac{1}{4}\left(\innerproduct vv-2\innerproduct vw+\innerproduct ww\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\innerproduct vv+\frac{1}{2}\innerproduct ww\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(\pnorm v{}^{2}+\pnorm w{}^{2}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The harder part is showing that if a norm that satisfies the parallelogram
 identity, there exists an inner product that induces such a norm.
 To do so, first define a map
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v,w\right):=\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v-w}{}^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

 and observe that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(v,v\right)=\pnorm v{}^{2}\geq0
\]

\end_inset

and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,v\right)=0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $v=0$
\end_inset

 by the definiteness condition of norms.
 Moreover, observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(v,w\right)=\left(w,v\right)$
\end_inset

 since
\begin_inset Formula $\pnorm{v-w}{}=\pnorm{w-v}{}$
\end_inset

.
 Next, note that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v,u,w\in V$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(v+u,w\right) & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{v+u+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v+u-w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{u+v}{}^{2}+\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2}+\pnorm{u+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm u{}^{2}-\pnorm v{}^{2}-\pnorm w{}^{2}\right.\\
 & \ \ \ \ \left.\ \ \ -\pnorm{u+v}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v-w}{}-\pnorm{u-w}{}^{2}+\pnorm u{}^{2}+\pnorm v{}^{2}+\pnorm w{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v-w}{}^{2}\right)+\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{u+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{u-w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(v,w\right)+\left(u,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:polarization"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 which proves additive linearity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
In order to establish multiplicative linearity on 
\begin_inset Formula $\R$
\end_inset

, we shall first demonstrate it on natural numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $\N$
\end_inset

, then on integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z},$
\end_inset

then on the rationals 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 and finally the entire real line.
 First, we show that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\N:\left(nv,w\right)=n\left(v,w\right).$
\end_inset

 This follows from induction on additive linearity since
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(nv,w\right) & =\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}v,w\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(v,w\right)\\
 & =n\left(v,w\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Next, to show that multiplicative linearity holds over 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z},$
\end_inset

 all we have to show is that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(0v,w\right)=0
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(-v,w\right)=-\left(v,w\right).
\]

\end_inset

The first follows on inspection; for the second, note
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(-v,w\right) & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{w-v}{}^{2}-\pnorm{-\left(v+w\right)}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{4}\left(\pnorm{v-w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v+w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =-\left(v,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second equality follows from absolute homogeneity of norms.
 To extend the multiplicative linearity to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

, consider an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $q\in\mathds{Q}$
\end_inset

 and note that by definition 
\begin_inset Formula $q=\frac{a}{b},\left(a,b\right)\in\mathds{Z}\times\left(\mathds{Z}\setminus\left\{ 0\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(qv,w\right) & =\left(\frac{a}{b}v,w\right)\\
 & =a\left(\frac{v}{b},w\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4}\left(\pnorm{\frac{v}{b}+w}{}^{2}-\pnorm{\frac{v}{b}-w}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4}\left(\pnorm{\frac{b}{b}\left(\frac{v}{b}+w\right)}{}^{2}-\pnorm{\frac{b}{b}\left(\frac{v}{b}-w\right)}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{4b^{2}}\left(\pnorm{v+bw}{}^{2}-\pnorm{v-bw}{}^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{b^{2}}\left(v,bw\right)\\
 & =\frac{a}{b}\left(v,w\right)\\
 & =q\left(v,w\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where we used the linearity on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathds{Z}$
\end_inset

